e, Devon, England"},"en":{"1540–1596":"1540–1596","1545–Female":"1545–Deceased","1565–Male":"1565–Deceased","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1545":"1545","1565":"1565","1596":"1596","1540":"1540","1549":"1549",", , Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Barnstaple, North Devon district, Devonshire, England":"Barnstaple, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Maxey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in Northamptonshire, so named from the Old English personal name <i>Maccus</i> + Old English <i>ēg</i> ‘island’.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Macasa</b> ‘descendant of <i>Macus</i>’, a personal name of uncertain origin. It may be a variant of   Magnus  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Maxcy","meanings":["English: variant of   Maxey  ."]},{"name":"Magnus","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Bernd, Egon, Erwin, Kurt, Otto, Reinhard, Volker, Wilhelm, Wolfgang.","German, Flemish, and Walloon: from the personal name <i>Magnus</i>, which is from the Latin adjective <i>magnus</i> ‘great’ or a Latinized form of a short form of ancient Germanic compound names based on the element <i>magan</i> ‘strength, might’. The name was borne by several early Christian saints, including St. Magnus (8th century), a monk in St. Gallen in Switzerland and missionary in Allgäu in southern Germany, whose real name was <i>Magnoald</i>. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine). In Belgium, it may also be a Latinized (humanistic) form of Walloon   Legrand  .","English, Scottish, Swedish, Danish, Norwegian, and North German: from the Scandinavian personal name <i>Magnus</i>, borne by Magnus the Good (died 1047), king of Norway and Denmark, who was named for the Emperor Charlemagne, Latin <i>Carolus Magnus</i> ‘Charles the Great’, under the impression that <i>Magnus</i> was a personal name. The name spread from Norway to the eastern Scandinavian royal houses, and became popular all over Scandinavia and thence in the English Danelaw. It has also been adopted as a Jewish name."]},{"name":"Maxie","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Maxey  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":9,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":18,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":29,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Maxey was born in 1540, in Kent, England. He had at least 1 son with Anne Goode. He died in 1596, in Barnstaple, Devon, England, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1540–1596":"1540–1596","1545–Female":"1545–Surnud","1565–Male":"1565–Surnud","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1545":"1545","1565":"1565","1596":"1596","1540":"1540","1549":"1549",", , Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Barnstaple, North Devon district, Devonshire, England":"Barnstaple, Devon, England"},"fi":{"1540–1596":"1540–1596","1545–Female":"1545–Kuollut","1565–Male":"1565–Kuollut","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1545":"1545","1565":"1565","1596":"1596","1540":"1540","1549":"1549",", , Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Barnstaple, North Devon district, Devonshire, England":"Barnstaple, Devon, England"},"fr":{"1540–1596":"1540–1596","1545–Female":"1545–Décédée","1565–Male":"1565–Décédé","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1545":"1545","1565":"1565","1596":"1596","1540":"1540","1549":"1549",", , Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, Angleterre","Kent, England":"Kent, Angleterre","Barnstaple, North Devon district, Devonshire, England":"Barnstaple, Devon, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"William Maxey est né en 1540, à Kent, Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Anne Goode. Il est décédé en 1596, à Barnstaple, Devon, Angleterre, à l’âge de 56 ans."},"de":{"1540–1596":"1540–1596","1545–Female":"1545–Verstorben","1565–Male":"1565–Verstorben","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1545":"1545","1565":"1565","1596":"1596","1540":"1540","1549":"1549",", , Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Barnstaple, North Devon district, Devonshire, England":"Barnstaple, Devon, England","lifeSu